ious design and an embrace of various phenomenon that emerge without intention or deliberate human guidance. This diffuse and complex body of theories discarded many of the cultural presuppositions of the time, shunning the traditions of modern design in favor of the wisdom, freedom, and self-organizing capacity of the market. Fontenot reveals the little-known commonalities between the aesthetic deregulation sought by ostensibly liberal thinkers and Hayek’s more controversial conception of state power, detailing what this unexplored affinity means for our conceptions of political liberalism. Non-Design thoroughly recasts conventional views of postwar architecture and urbanism, as well as liberal and libertarian philosophies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aArchitecturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aArchitecture, Moderny20th century. 0aCity planningxHistoryy20th century. 0aDesignxPhilosophy. 0aLiberalism. 0aLibertarianism. 7aARCHITECTURE / General.2bisacsh  anon-design, central design, liberalism, spontaneous order, free market, Friedrich Hayek, Jane Jacobs, Ernst Gombrich, Robert Venturi, Reyner Banham.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226752471423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226752471/original  a978-3-11-073919-0  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles